text.tspan: Proposed System: TeKno (Text-to-Knowledge)
The main purpose of TeKno is to analyze a source text
and extract knowledge, first in the form of a
graph database, then from that in the form of a Prolog
knowledge base. This allows us to perform
reasoning and make the user interact with the formalized
knowledge.
TeKno, also, allows the user to read XML files that
contain a formalized graph as a form of integration
with ConNektion.
The software can be divided into two main parts: facts
and graph extraction developed in Java and
the reasoning on the extracted facts developed in
Prolog.
In this section, we will illustrate the overall functioning
of the system.
Pipeline
The process of extraction of knowledge from natural
language text can be divided into the following
phases (represented in the image below):
The text is first annotated with the methods made
available by the Stanford CoreNLP library.
This allows us to access to various annotations e.g.
pos tagging, named entities and so on.
With the annotations, we can access coreference chains
found in the text and use them to
substitute all the coreference terms with a single
name thus obtaining a new text with
resolved coreferences.
We then re-annotated the text, to account for the
substitutions made in the previous step.
